	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU CFP: reporting goes by the board</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> Undeclared landings, misreporting and under-reporting of catches from EU fishing fleets are widespread, according to one of the main findings of the 2004 Fisheries &quot;Compliance Scoreboar &quot;dublished at the end of July 2004 by the EC.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> The Compliance Scoreboard provides information in five areas: catches, fleet, funding, market traceability and monitoring/control activities. This includes information relating to EU activities in third-country, notably ACP waters. EU member states must submit reports providing catch data (E and F reports) on a quarterly basis to the EC, detailing the quantities of each species taken from third-country waters and the high seas that is landed in their territories, either by vessels flying their flag or the flag of another member state.</p><p>
 A very low level of compliance has been observed with regard to these E and F reports. The scoreboard concludes that &quot;as for E and F reports, despite some progress, the situation remains unsatisfactory with regard to catches in non-EU waters. The EU is fully committed to ensuring sustainability wherever its fishing fleets operate and the monitoring of catches beyond EU waters has a crucial role to play in meeting this objective.?<br /> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/press/inf04_35_en.htm" target="_self">EC press release, July 27th 2004</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/fisheries/news_corner/press/inf04_34_en.htm" target="_self">Main findings of the &quot;Compliance Scoreboard?, EC press release, Jul...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> A notable understatement of the compliance scoreboard report is that &quot;Given the continued gaps observed in member state &quot;snforcement activities, the data sent to the commission may not accurately reflect reality.? What the scoreboard shows very clearly is an alarming lack of commitment amongst EU member states fishing in ACP waters to provide data on these activities to the EC.</p><p> This underscores both the need for ACP countries to obtain such data themselves, and the extent of the task they face. Obtaining data on EU catches is crucial for ACP countries, particularly for making accurate stock assessments, and sustainable resource allocation to the various users. In addition, detailed and reliable information is required on the quantities and value of fish catches made by EU vessels in order to establish the levels of financial compensation due to ACP countries from EU-ACP fisheries agreements.</p><p> The improvement of the monitoring and control of EU fishing activities clearly needs to become a central part of EU-ACP discussions on establishing fisheries partnerships.</p><p> It must also be noted that while decisions regarding fisheries measures are taken at EU level, enforcement of these measures is the responsibility of EU member states. In the case of EU vessels fishing in ACP waters under bilateral fisheries agreements, EU member states must ensure that all the fishing vessels flying their flags comply with the measures adopted in that agreement. The results of the scoreboard show that all too often the agreement is not honoured.</p><p> The future EU control agency, that will be based in Vigo (Spain), needs to take a leading role in the task of improving ACP countrie &quot;sccess to reliable catch data.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

